  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">For human rights training and advocacy. Batwa are indigenous people in Burundi. In 2011, their population was estimated to be at about 80 000 or 1 % of the population. Batwa are the poorest and most discriminated ethnic minority in Burundi, and their health situation is poor: the life expectancy is very low and infant mortality high. The lack of land rights and the poor food security are major causes of Batwa&apos;s a weak position. Because of old beliefs women and girls are in a very vulnerable position. Traditionally, the Batwa communities were hunter-gatherer cultures, and were both socially and sexually very equal. The project aims to promote Batwa rights through national advocacy and by informing and educating the Batwa about their indigenous and minority rights. The aim of the advocacy campaign is to influence decision-makers and media representatives about Batwa rights. The project will focus in particular on the identity card, which will bring by the promotion of the rights and benefits and the information about human rights violations experienced by the Batwa. The project&apos;s direct beneficiaries are the Kayanza, Kirundo, Bujumbura, Makamba, Gitega, Bubanza and Bururi provinces</narrative>
  </description>
